		<td><b>Cut the CIC</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Does the cic pin4 mod really require cutting?  The videos I've just pull it out.  Can it be plugged back in?

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>koitsu</b> [ Mon Aug 19, 2013 8:18 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: Cut the CIC</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Lifting the pin (examples: <a href="http://www.damomonster.com/Mod_Images/Sega_Saturn/Pin79.jpg" class="postlink">#1</a> <a href="http://longhornengineer.com/images/howto/videomods/Atari2600/light6switch/DSCN4430.jpg" class="postlink">#2</a> <a href="http://www.smspower.org/uploads/Development/32step1.jpg" class="postlink">#3</a>) and cutting the pin are effectively/functionally the same thing.<br /><br />The reason people cut it (rather than lift it) is for simplicity; it's a lot easier to just cut the pin with some wire snips when it's already soldered into place (<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:10nes.JPG" class="postlink">example</a>).  Otherwise you have to desolder the entire chip (all the pins), remove it, lift the pin, then reinsert/resolder the chip in place.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


